The greatest sages of the Talmud never worked alone.

99
00:12:10,623 --> 00:12:16,384
They operated in chavruta, an Aramaic which is chaver, meaning friend or peer.

100
00:12:17,984 --> 00:12:30,587
Now the best chavruta, a study partner, this is a Jewish tradition that continues to this day, a study partner that you learn with on a regular basis, is not someone who always agrees with you on every issue.

101
00:12:30,707 --> 00:12:38,248
In fact, the best chavruta is the one who shows you when you're wrong, who tells you when you've got the wrong end of the stick.

102
00:12:39,693 --> 00:12:56,845
There's a line from Mishlei, from Proverbs, that says, barzel b'barzel yachad, iron sharpens iron, and this is the founding principle of learning and seeing the world through the lens of chavruta, principled partnership and opposition.

103
00:12:59,867 --> 00:13:07,193
Two of the most famous rabbis of the Mishnaic period, the Talmud, were named Shammai and Hillel,

104
00:13:08,730 --> 00:13:15,657
If you've heard of either of them, you've probably heard of Hillel and not Shammai, because Hillel takes precedence, generally.

105
00:13:16,458 --> 00:13:24,466
Tractate Erevin of the Talmud says that for three years, Beit Shammai, the students in the tradition of Shammai, and Beit Hillel,

106
00:13:25,046 --> 00:13:29,508
the students learning in the tradition of Rabbi Hillel, pressed their arguments.

107
00:13:30,008 --> 00:13:36,791
Ultimately, a bat kol, a divine voice, proclaimed, Elu ve'elu divrei elohim chayim.

108
00:13:37,091 --> 00:13:39,912
These and those are the words of the living God.

109
00:13:40,813 --> 00:13:43,734
However, the ruling is in accordance with Hillel.

110
00:13:45,655 --> 00:13:51,017
Now, why does Hillel get this privilege of taking precedence?

111
00:13:51,938 --> 00:14:06,403
He's the one who ruled, many of you may be familiar with the holiday of Hanukkah, that the number of candles should go up from day to day so that the light increases in the world over the course of the day, whereas Shammai went the other way, starting with eight and counting down.

112
00:14:07,343 --> 00:14:10,024
The argument being, we always go up in holiness.

113
00:14:11,890 --> 00:14:15,897
So why are the words of Hillel prioritized?

114
00:14:15,997 --> 00:14:21,165
Because the students of Hillel were civil and forbearing with each other and with their opponents.

115
00:14:21,666 --> 00:14:24,932
Only their own statements, but those of Shammai as well.

116
00:14:26,464 --> 00:14:46,796
This is a tradition that's carried on in Judaism, a multivocal tradition, where the reason the Talmud is so long, it's something almost 3,000 pages long, is because all of the arguments for and against, no matter which ultimately took effect, are recorded, are studied, are thought about, and sharpened.

117
00:14:47,076 --> 00:14:48,237
Iron sharpens iron.

118
00:14:50,238 --> 00:14:53,841
Now, if you don't have the right chavruta, the one who will tell you,

119
00:14:54,628 --> 00:14:55,549
when you're off base.

120
00:14:56,449 --> 00:14:58,191
It can be literally fatal.

121
00:14:59,232 --> 00:15:04,636
